1) Interface Changes:
    - Interface is collection of abstract methods.
    - The methods which does not contains any body is called abstract methods.
    - Interface in Java is a blueprint that defines what a class must do (methods), not how it does it.
    - Suppose we implement any interface we need to write abstract methods implementation inside the interface in the classes in which we are implementing the interface
    - Implementing interface is nothing but overriding the abstract methods.
    - Suppose we are adding one more abstract method in the interface so classes who implemented that interface will get compilation
      error(need to write implementation of abstract methods) so that is why default and static methods comes in front.
    - diff between the default and static method is that we can override the default method but we cannot override static methods
    - also we can call default methods using the object but for static we call it using the class name or that interface name.
    - also if we have to concrete method we need to use the default keyword in it.






